```

Or with `uv`:

```bash
uv pip install -r requirements.txt
```

## Choose your model provider

The generated app is **provider-agnostic** ‚Äî it routes through LangChain's
`init_chat_model`, so any provider that LangChain supports works. Set
`DEEPAGENTS_MODEL` to the matching `provider:model` identifier and provide
that provider's credentials.

| Provider | `DEEPAGENTS_MODEL` example | Required env vars | Extra install |
|---|---|---|---|
| Anthropic (default) | `anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-6` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | ‚Äî (already in `requirements.txt`) |
| OpenAI | `openai:gpt-4o` | `OPENAI_API_KEY` | ‚Äî (already in `requirements.txt`) |
| Azure OpenAI | `azure_openai:<deployment-name>` | `AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY`, `AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT`, `OPENAI_API_VERSION`, `AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT_NAME` | ‚Äî (already in `requirements.txt`) |
| AWS Bedrock | `bedrock_converse:anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0` | `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID`, `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`, `AWS_REGION` | `pip install langchain-aws` |
| Google Vertex | `google_vertexai:gemini-1.5-pro` | `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` | `pip install langchain-google-vertexai` |

> **Azure OpenAI note** ‚Äî `DEEPAGENTS_MODEL=azure_openai:<deployment-name>` uses
> the Azure *deployment name*, not the OpenAI model id. The `langchain-openai`
> package reads `AZURE_OPENAI_*` env vars automatically; no code changes needed.

Copy `.env.example` to `.env`, uncomment the provider block you want, and fill
in credentials. `langgraph dev` loads `.env` automatically.

